"(1) (i) The cold blue glow of the inner observation dome filtered through the reinforced plexiglass, painting the sterile corridor in a spectral light. Zoe pressed her palm against the control panel, her breath fogging in the recycled air as the alert flashed red across the holo readout. Beyond the reinforced viewport, the Mercury twilight shimmered with the faintest hint of auroral flicker, but the silence was broken only by the hum of life support and the distant thump of a maintenance drone. She knew the schedule by heart—no cryo-pods were due for check cycles today—but the warning tone in her ears was unmistakable: integrity compromised.\n(2) (ii) (i) On , watched in horror as the cryo-pod’s containment field flickered and fractured along a jagged line of blue light. The glass shell shuddered, spiderweb cracks spreading rapidly as the internal pressure gauge screamed past its red threshold. Her hands trembled as she initiated the emergency lockdown protocol, the cold metal of the pod’s access hatch groaning open in slow, inexorable motion. The sterile scent of antifreeze and ozone filled the air as the breach widened, and Zoe realized with sudden, sharp clarity that she was witnessing history—her eyes locked on the failing barrier at , the only place in the system where such a catastrophe could unfold. Mercury Twilight Observatory. June 14, 2225. Zoe Brown. witnessed a cryo-pod integrity breach."